    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-20T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="178"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–2054: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-20T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 20, 1954—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>89. Repeated information Department [<gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss>]
                    264, Tokyo 76. For <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAH1">Dean</persName>. Tokyo pass <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1"
                        >CINCUNC</gloss>. Department pass Defense.</p>
                <list>
                    <item>
                        <p>Part I—re Seoul’s 99, sent Department 1208, repeated information Tokyo
                                716.<note n="1" xml:id="d178fn1">Dated May 19, <ref target="#pg_291"
                                    >p. 291</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Note May 19 letter from Prime Minister to <persName corresp="#p_DAH1"
                                >Dean</persName> proposes simultaneous release statement of
                            principles.</p>
                        <p>Hope you can impress on President <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                                >Rhee</persName> and Prime Minister on suitable occasion that such
                            release procedure highly undesirable since would diminish impact on
                            world opinion and would evade US-<gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                            responsibility coordinate with other 14 delegations at Geneva. Proper
                            procedure following US-<gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> agreement on
                            statement would be referral to group of nine at Geneva, which would in
                            turn report to meeting of 16, which would then coordinate presentation
                            statement at plenary conference meeting to assure maximum effect.</p>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <p>Part II—re <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 258, sent Seoul 88,
                            repeated information Tokyo 74.<note n="2" xml:id="d178fn2">Not printed.
                                It said that there would be a plenary session on Korea on Saturday
                                and that the delegation hoped there would be a meeting of the group
                                of nine on Friday. (396.1 GE/5–1954)</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>At Saturday<note n="3" xml:id="d178fn3">May 22.</note> Korean plenary
                                <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou En-lai</persName> inscribed to
                            speak first.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
